ø4==ø1About this NFO
   This  NFO  is still not completely complete  :)  It has been put out for
    general  consumption in order to answer  most questions asked, but more
    information will become available as the party approaches. Please refer
    to  our  web-page (coven.au.demoscene.net)  for  the latest information
    (including the latest version of this NFO (this is version 2.0)).

ø4==ø1Introduction
   Coven  '98 will be better than any other Coven so far seen. At long last
    a  suitable sponsor has been found who  can provide us with the support
    we  need to make a demo party everything  it should be. We plan to make
    Coven so annihilatingly attractive to you that you'll be quite happy to
    sell  your un-born kid's kidneys to  an backyard Indian organ clinic to
    pay for tickets and transport. Read on for details.






ø4==ø1Vital Statistics
   Coven  will  feature an indoor  ceiling-mounted digital projector, a 3x3
    51cm Videowall. Outdoor projector was never procured by Ngapartji ;)
   Built-in surround sound speaker system in the main party room.
   Cheap/Free drinks and chips on sale through-out the event. (Jolt/Coke/etc)
   Half-price Pizza.
   Transport subsidies have been arranged.
   $10/night share accomodation in a nearby (1minute crawl ;) hotel.
   A  very  high bandwidth (10Mbps) internet  connection, and a local 10gig
    web/ftp/irc server.
   Approximately 10-15 PentiumII-233mhz machines for general use.
   Coven will be located within crawling distance of a pub, as well as many
    other fine restaurants and cafes.







ø4==ø1What is Coven?
   Coven  is  an annual party held  in  Adelaide, South Australia. Begun in
    1995, it has steadily increased in magnitude and popularity.
   It is based around the so-called 'demoscene'. A loosely related group of
    people  from  all  over the world  who  spend  their idle time creating
    programs that involve original music, art and 'effects'.
   Coven  is  an  opportunity (a three  day,  24hr opportunity) for all the
    people in Australia who consider themselves a part of this demoscene to
    meet, often face to face for the first time, socialise, compete against
    each  other in the various demo-related competitions and generally have
    a lot of fun.
   Typically Coven involves around 50-100 enthusiasts (many with computers)
    inside  a large hall or auditorium, a large digital projector and sound
    system for viewing demos/music/art and a large amount of fun :)






ø4==ø1Where is Coven?
   Coven '98 is being held at the Ngapartji Multimedia center (who are also
    our  main  sponsor),  which is  a  part-government  funded high-tech IT
    facility  who's main purpose is to help  pump life into the IT industry
    in  Adelaide through public awareness campaigns and investment support.
    Ngapartji  is located in one of the most populous areas of the Adelaide
    CBD,  Rundle  Street.  Rundle Street is  noted  for  it's vast array of
    cafes,  restaurants and 'trendy' stores (and Ngapartji! :). It's pretty
    much located just East of the very centre of the City and is one of the
    prime  night-time locations for the younger generation of today's world
    :).









ø4==ø1When is Coven?
   Retaining  its  Winter party beginnings, Coven  will  occur in the first
    half  of  July  (8th-11th to be precise).  We  have  timed the dates to
    ensure  that  as many university and  school holiday breaks as possible
    will  coincide with Coven. It will begin mid-week (hence finishing on a
    Saturday)  to  ensure all participants have  ample time to recover from
    the  marathon (and get back to  where they live for those interstaters)
    before the beginnning of the next week. :)
   The  doors  will be open to the  ticket-holders at noon on Wednesday the
    8th  of July. The last event of the  party will be on the Friday night,
    allowing  until noon on Saturday the 11th  of July for everyone to have
    cleaned up and moved out.








ø4==ø1How much is Coven?
   That  depends  on  where you are travelling  from,  how much you eat and
    drink,  whether  you  routinely burn $100  bills  and whether you win a
    prize :).
   The  ticket-price  will  most likely be  near  the $20 mark. All revenue
    raised  from ticket-sales will be used  to pay for expenses not covered
    by  our sponsors, with the remaining (hopefully a large percentage will
    remain) money put into the prize pool for the competitions (see below).
   We  expect either free or heavily discounted soft drink (coke/jolt/etc),
    and cheap 'snacks' (chips). During business hours at Ngapartji you will
    also  be able to purchase tea, coffee and other beverages (at Ngapartji
    retail prices, -- MAYBE -- some discount will apply)
   We're  also negotiating possible discount  vouchers for some surrounding
    restaurants and cafes.
   If  you  need  to  travel from interstate  to  attend  Coven, you may be
    getting  some  subsidies  :)  Please see  the  travel  section for more
    information.



ø4==ø1What to bring?
   Here's a quick-list of everything you could bring:

     - Yourself
     - Heaps of your friends :)
     - A computer
NEWS: Coaxial cabling is NOT required, we'll be supplying hubs and cabling.
       (twisted pair)
     - Powerboard/extension cords
     - Beroccas, aspirin/etc for dealing with the length of time you'll be
        awake :)
     - Pillow :)
     - Maybe a change of clothes if you plan to stay the whole event.







ø4==ø1What NOT to bring?
   Coven  98 is an all-ages event. Alcohol will be prohibited from entering
    the partyplace. Anyone found with illegal drugs will be reported to the
    police  immediately. Anyone found intoxicated or acting in a disorderly
    manner   will  be  removed  from   the  party.  Please  understand  the
    responsibilities  us organisers are taking up here, it would be a shame
    to see someone's equipment damaged or maybe even an injury occur due to
    someone   acting   improperly  and   inconsiderately   with  regard  to
    intoxicating  substances. There is a pub directly across from the party
    place,  you  are  welcome to spend  your  evenings  there (you won't be
    allowed back in until your at least acting sobre ;).

   We  would  like to discourage people  from bringing excessive amounts of
    their own food into the partyplace. Mainly because we're doing our best
    to  give  you cheap food/drink, but  also because we have limited space
    and excessive luggage (it does add up) will cause a bit of a squeeze.

   Naturally  we also don't want to see tables/chairs, we will be providing
    chairs and tables at the party place.

ø4==ø1What NOT to bring? (continued)
   With regard to equipment, keep it to the bare minimum. We won't have the
    deskspace for laser printers and flatbed scanners ok? :)

   Attendees  are also advised that there is a risk of damage to equipment,
    accidents  do  happen.  So  if you've  got  some  really nifty piece of
    equipment that cost you a lot of money, you might be better off leaving
    it home.












ø4==ø1Security at Coven
   There will be an employee of Ngapartji attending the party at ALL times,
    on  top of that at least one organiser (or assistant organiser) will be
    present  to  handle any problems you  might have. During the evenings a
    security  patrol will keep a check on  the party, and there is a police
    station very nearby.

   The  past  has been quite pleasant  with regards to stolen equipment. To
    date  not one case of intentional theft has occured at any of the three
    past  Covens. However things do get lost from time to time and there is
    usually  a  small  stash of  left-behind  equipment that the organisers
    always  find  at the end of the party  :) The best thing to do is label
    all  your equipment clearly, this includes cables (you wouldn't believe
    how many power cords and network cables we pick up at the end each year
    :).  This way we can simplify and speed up the returning of property to
    it's  rightful  owners. Naturally you should  always make sure you know
    where all your equipment is, and try to ensure that someone you know by
    name  is  watching  after your equipment  at  all times (if you can't).
    There  have  been  cases where  machines  were  accidently unplugged or
    moved/bumped/used  without consent because  there wasn't anyone keeping
ø4==ø1Security at Coven (continued)
    an eye out for their equipment.

   We may be implementing some kind of systematic labelling upon entry this
    year.















